  "prompt": "What is the time complexity for reversing a string through recursion?",
  "response": "Reversing a string through recursion involves breaking the original string down into smaller substrings and then concatenating them in reverse order. To analyze the time complexity, we consider how many recursive calls are made and the amount of work done in each call.\n\nFor a string of length \\( n \\):\n\n1. **Recursive Calls**:\n   Each recursion step creates a new function call, typically breaking the string down by one character. Therefore, there are \\( n \\) recursive calls.\n\n2. **Work Done in Each Call**:\n   In each call, the work done generally includes concatenating a substring and possibly passing parameters. The concatenation operation itself can take linear time relative to the length of the substring being concatenated. However, in many implementations, this can be considered constant time, as the substring lengths involved in each immediate recursive step are relatively small.\n\nOverall, the recursive approach is effectively making \\( n \\) calls, each performing a constant amount of work. Thus, the time complexity for reversing a string through recursion is:\n\n\\[ O(n) \\]\n\nIt\u2019s also worth noting that recursion can introduce additional overhead due to maintaining the call stack, which in practical applications, might result in performance considerations beyond pure time complexity analysis.",
